eland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1342–":"1342–Deceased","1342–Male":"1342–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1346–1379":"1346–1379","1367–Male":"1367–Deceased","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1316–Male":"1316–Deceased","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1316":"1316","1379":"1379","1346":"1346","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1342":"1342","1320":"1320","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Farleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwood, , Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England,":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Raleigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Raleigh (House) in Pilton (Devon), recorded as <i>Radeleia</i> in 1086 and <i>Rawlegh</i> in 1535. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>rǣge</i> ‘roe deer’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: variant of   Riley  .","History: The English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh (1554–1618) was born in Hayes Barton, Devon, into a family of Devon gentry. He was related to most of the West Country's important families, including that of Sir Francis Drake. His half-brother was the explorer Sir Humphrey Gilbert. In 1578 Raleigh was granted a patent to explore and colonize “unknown lands” in America. In the 1580s he was granted extensive estates in Munster (Ireland), in reward for his suppression of the Desmond Rebellions."],"variants":[{"name":"Raley","meanings":["English: variant of   Raleigh  ."]},{"name":"Rawleigh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Orlo.","English: variant of   Raleigh  , reflecting a common pronunciation."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":113,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John de Raleigh II was born in 1342, in Farleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Henry Rawleigh, was 26 and his mother, Isabella de Beaumont, was 22. He married Elizabeth Bamvile. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in England."},"et":{"1342–":"1342–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1346–1379":"1346–1379","1367–Male":"1367–Surnud","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1316":"1316","1379":"1379","1346":"1346","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1342":"1342","1320":"1320","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Farleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwood, , Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England,":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1342–":"1342–Kuollut","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1346–1379":"1346–1379","1367–Male":"1367–Kuollut","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1316–Male":"1316–Kuollut","1320–1361":"1320–1361","1316":"1316","1379":"1379","1346":"1346","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1342":"1342","1320":"1320","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1428":"1428","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Farleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Cornwood, , Devon, England":"Cornwood, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England,":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1342–":"1342–Décédé","1342–Male":"1342–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1346–1379":"1346–1379","1367–Male":"1367–Décédé","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1316–Male":"1316–Décédé","1320–1361":"132